1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:17,533
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:17,513 --> 00:00:26,102
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambodasa.

3
00:00:26,121 --> 00:00:32,268
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

4
00:00:32,289 --> 00:00:37,134
So I'm looking at the Dhammapada number 90 and it's about what makes an arahat.

5
00:00:37,375 --> 00:00:39,517
So it gives us some indication, shall we say.

6
00:00:40,057 --> 00:00:41,558
So I shall do the little chanting.

7
00:00:42,621 --> 00:00:45,664
Gatadino isukasa

8
00:00:46,183 --> 00:01:11,763
And the translation from Jill Fronsdale is, For someone at the journey's end, freed of sorrow, liberated in all ways, released from all bonds, no fever exists.

9
00:01:11,783 --> 00:01:13,305
And Thanissaro says,

10
00:01:14,094 --> 00:01:38,195
in one who has gone the full distance so we always like to say something different is free from sorrow fully released in all respects has abandoned all the bonds no fever is found so okay we'll go into exactly what all that means but let's look at the little story which sometimes throws light

11
00:01:40,555 --> 00:01:46,545
Now on one occasion, Devadatta tried to kill the Buddha by pushing a big rock on him from Vulture's Peak.

12
00:01:47,947 --> 00:01:53,736
The rock struck a ledge on the side of the mountain and a splinter struck the big toe of the Buddha.

13
00:01:54,957 --> 00:01:58,123
He was taken to the mangrove grove monastery of Jivaka.

14
00:01:58,623 --> 00:02:06,376
Now there, Jivaka, the renowned physician, attended to him and applied some medicine on the toe and bandaged it.

15
00:02:07,319 --> 00:02:13,907
Jivaka then left to see another patient in town but promised to return and remove the bandage in the evening.

16
00:02:14,907 --> 00:02:21,776
Now when Jivaka tried to return the city gates were already closed and he could not attend to the Buddha.

17
00:02:22,717 --> 00:02:31,268
He was very upset because if the bandage was not removed in time the whole body would be affected and the Buddha would be very ill.

18
00:02:32,242 --> 00:02:35,449
Now the Buddha knew that Jivaka would not be able to attend him.

19
00:02:35,990 --> 00:02:41,038
So he asked Venerable Ananda to remove the bandage and found the wound was healed.

20
00:02:42,461 --> 00:02:51,518
Jivaka came to the monastery early next morning to inquire whether he had felt great pain and distress the previous night.

21
00:02:51,717 --> 00:03:02,751
And the Buddha replied, Jivaka, ever since I attained enlightenment, I had the ability to stop pain and distress at any time whenever I needed to do so.

22
00:03:03,792 --> 00:03:07,736
Then the Buddha explained the nature of the mind of the enlightened one.

23
00:03:08,318 --> 00:03:11,100
And that's what this verse is.

24
00:03:11,121 --> 00:03:12,763
It's interesting that he says,

25
00:03:14,481 --> 00:03:40,741
pain doesn't feel pain or he can he can stop the feeling of pain now i had a student who got um kidney stones and and they're said to be extremely painful and so he was in a e and he decided to sit in meditation and the pain disappeared and when the nurse came to uh take him uh you know take him to the doctor it reappeared again

26
00:03:40,873 --> 00:04:02,021
so so there's something about where your attention is but i also think that the body does have an ability to anesthetize itself um i believe i'm writing saying that you know in war if you're shot or if you know if you have a serious injury you don't actually feel it you feel it afterwards so

27
00:04:03,925 --> 00:04:06,513
But the Buddha says he has the power to stop that anyway.

28
00:04:06,873 --> 00:04:09,542
And distress, of course, would be a mental state.

29
00:04:11,167 --> 00:04:12,973
He would be free of that anyway.

30
00:04:14,287 --> 00:04:22,915
On that point, of course, there is the Arahant who is suffering severely, very painful feelings from an illness.

31
00:04:23,375 --> 00:04:31,644
He's quite old and he goes to the Buddha and tells him, you know, I'm going to take the knife, which was a way of saying he's going to, you know, commit suicide.

32
00:04:32,103 --> 00:04:34,646
And the Buddha simply said, well, do as you think is fit.

33
00:04:35,086 --> 00:04:35,567
And he did.

34
00:04:36,228 --> 00:04:38,149
He committed suicide, took his own life.

35
00:04:38,790 --> 00:04:40,411
So that's something to ponder about.

36
00:04:48,728 --> 00:04:58,416
So if we look at some of the words here, the gata dino, gata just means having done the path.

37
00:04:58,497 --> 00:05:01,059
So it is a fairly straightforward translation.

38
00:05:02,319 --> 00:05:04,502
Visokasa means without sorrow.

39
00:05:04,581 --> 00:05:17,233
Now this soka actually seemingly comes from the Vedic shoka, which actually means the flame of a fire, but then later had the sense of burning grief.

40
00:05:17,904 --> 00:05:20,387
So very strong words here.

41
00:05:21,908 --> 00:05:29,536
And then he's free from these bonds, which we'll come to in a minute.

42
00:05:29,596 --> 00:05:31,937
They're a special classification.

43
00:05:33,279 --> 00:05:41,627
And the word used for the ending of sorrow, parilaho, one who has free from sorrow.

44
00:05:44,470 --> 00:05:45,370
Where have I got that now?

45
00:05:45,612 --> 00:05:46,151
I've lost it.

46
00:05:46,673 --> 00:05:47,153
Oh, here we are.

47
00:05:49,798 --> 00:05:51,081
Oh dear, dear, dear.

48
00:05:51,360 --> 00:05:52,122
Where have you gone?

49
00:05:53,944 --> 00:05:57,269
Just when you want to find a word, it's disappeared.

50
00:06:02,916 --> 00:06:07,423
Anyway, that strong word, free from fever.

51
00:06:07,903 --> 00:06:10,627
It's a very strong word, free from fever.

52
00:06:11,509 --> 00:06:14,052
And it would seem to me that...

53
00:06:15,651 --> 00:06:28,608
We're talking about sort of fairly extreme emotional states here, but really somebody who's fully liberated wouldn't feel any negative feelings.

54
00:06:28,987 --> 00:06:31,891
Now that doesn't mean to say that sorrow would not be felt.

55
00:06:32,451 --> 00:06:36,197
Sorrow is that heart connection with the suffering of somebody else.

56
00:06:36,997 --> 00:06:39,060
So I can't imagine that disappearing.

57
00:06:40,728 --> 00:06:48,454
But the big thing is, of course, is that the arahat is liberated from these ganta.

58
00:06:48,475 --> 00:06:49,860
Now a ganta is a,

59
00:06:52,759 --> 00:06:54,461
is a knot or a bond.

60
00:06:55,142 --> 00:06:57,906
And the full word is kaya ganta.

61
00:06:58,305 --> 00:07:02,550
Kaya means body, and it refers both to the physical and the mental body.

62
00:07:03,031 --> 00:07:11,100
So it's basically saying those things that keep you tied to this form of becoming, this form of existence.

63
00:07:12,380 --> 00:07:22,091
And the four ties, you won't be surprised by them, I don't think, are covetousness, abhija, vipada, which is ill will,

64
00:07:24,247 --> 00:07:27,170
An attachment to rules and rituals.

65
00:07:27,910 --> 00:07:55,403
and dogmatic fanaticism so now if we look at these they you'll see that they are all these lists of what is unwholesome in us like the five hindrances the ten fetters they're always rooted in the three unwholesome roots which is acquisitiveness aversion which remember includes both

66
00:07:55,382 --> 00:08:01,310
Aversion and its opposite, and it's sort of twin, which is fear.

67
00:08:01,812 --> 00:08:05,516
So fear and aversion and delusion.

68
00:08:06,497 --> 00:08:15,990
So the first one, abidja, is obviously to do with loba, that's the word for it, which is greed or acquisitiveness.

69
00:08:17,112 --> 00:08:20,757
But here, it gives a certain slant to it.

70
00:08:20,858 --> 00:08:23,060
It's called, you know, covetousness.

71
00:08:23,327 --> 00:08:25,651
You always want what somebody else has.

72
00:08:25,690 --> 00:08:40,812
Sometimes when you're in line with monks for food and people put things into your bowl, you're often tempted to see what the other person got which you didn't get.

73
00:08:43,898 --> 00:08:54,788
So it's that sort of wanting, not only just wanting something, coveting something, but this added thing of wanting what somebody else has.

74
00:08:55,307 --> 00:09:02,134
And you can see how greed creates that sort of dissatisfaction, that sort of conflict.

75
00:09:02,634 --> 00:09:12,724
As soon as you say, I want what you have, you're putting yourself up in a sense in competition with the other person or against the other person.

76
00:09:13,447 --> 00:09:18,410
So already it's not a great particular mental state to develop.

77
00:09:21,412 --> 00:09:26,716
The next one, of course, is ill will, byāpāda, malevolence, ill will.

78
00:09:27,457 --> 00:09:45,394
So this gives it a more sort of active, rather than a sort of passive hatred, sort of an active form where when your heart feels hatred, it'll manifest in some angry way, in some way which is antagonistic, conflictual.

79
00:09:46,975 --> 00:09:50,658
So those two things have gone in the arahat.

80
00:09:53,440 --> 00:10:00,466
And the final ones, the final two there, the first one is an attachment to ritual, to rules and rituals.

81
00:10:00,826 --> 00:10:03,409
Now, does that mean that we shouldn't be doing any?

82
00:10:04,270 --> 00:10:07,974
No, it's really what we believe the ritual to be doing.

83
00:10:08,855 --> 00:10:20,746
So for instance, when we take refuges and precepts, it's really just creating an atmosphere within us of devotion, of commitment, of reminding ourselves what our path is.

84
00:10:21,537 --> 00:10:34,668
But if we were to believe that taking the Reference and Precept was quite enough and we don't have to do anything else, just light a few candles, say, you know, a Josh stick, say the Reference and Precepts and that's it, you know, I'll get on with my life.

85
00:10:35,628 --> 00:10:39,831
I'll keep on being as I am, then I think we'd be sorely disappointed.

86
00:10:40,673 --> 00:10:46,798
So it's a case of recognizing that there are bound to be rituals in our lives.

87
00:10:46,859 --> 00:10:51,283
In fact, we have rituals that we keep, just as the morning ablutions, for instance.

88
00:10:52,423 --> 00:10:57,849
There'll be a little ritual that we've performed for ourselves when we prepare our meals.

89
00:10:58,389 --> 00:11:03,794
So it's not as though rituals don't have a place in our lives.

90
00:11:05,496 --> 00:11:07,239
It's sort of an habitual thing.

91
00:11:07,539 --> 00:11:10,344
But I think what a ritual does is it gives it meaning.

92
00:11:10,924 --> 00:11:25,644
So rather than just slapping the food on the plate and chucking it down into the stomach, if one takes one's time with a little reflection and then eats mindfully, it gives it meaning.

93
00:11:25,965 --> 00:11:29,110
It gives it meaning in the fullness of our practice.

94
00:11:29,129 --> 00:11:31,452
And that's what a ritual is meant to do.

95
00:11:33,273 --> 00:11:38,138
When it comes to rules, there are overt and covert rules.

96
00:11:38,798 --> 00:11:46,086
So obviously when you go into somebody's house, it's presumed that you're not going to steal from them.

97
00:11:46,746 --> 00:11:53,913
It's like, that's a, should we say, an obvious rule, you might say.

98
00:11:54,214 --> 00:12:00,039
But there are also covert rules, like you don't move the furniture around when you're staying at somebody's house.

99
00:12:01,893 --> 00:12:05,557
I always remember, you know, I invited my mother to come and stay with me.

100
00:12:06,418 --> 00:12:15,447
And she did, she came and I had a flower, a flower pot with a flower flowering, you might say, in the front room.

101
00:12:15,488 --> 00:12:18,451
And when I came down, she'd moved it.

102
00:12:19,532 --> 00:12:26,820
And I, you know, it was just one of those things that your mother does that just presses the button.

103
00:12:28,284 --> 00:12:31,254
And I remember shouting at her, you know, this is my house, leave me alone.

104
00:12:31,736 --> 00:12:32,659
You know, it goes here.

105
00:12:33,423 --> 00:12:34,927
Sort of like a little kid.

106
00:12:35,870 --> 00:12:36,432
Ah, dear me.

107
00:12:37,096 --> 00:12:39,222
Wouldn't have been so bad if I weren't over 30.

108
00:12:42,292 --> 00:12:45,197
So there are these rules and regulations.

109
00:12:45,918 --> 00:12:50,164
Rules, of course, are what establishes an institution.

110
00:12:50,264 --> 00:12:51,967
Every institution has a set of rules.

111
00:12:52,568 --> 00:12:55,433
The big ones, like democracy, you've got your constitution.

112
00:12:56,716 --> 00:13:00,100
The monks have their own rules and regulations.

113
00:13:00,581 --> 00:13:01,524
So they have a place.

114
00:13:01,644 --> 00:13:02,325
But

115
00:13:02,304 --> 00:13:18,491
If I as a monastic were to say to myself, my job is to keep the rule absolutely perfectly and in so doing I will become enlightened, I again would be very disappointed because that is not an end in itself.

116
00:13:18,471 --> 00:13:28,855
And often you do meet monks who have that mentality because you get caught in this double bind, a catch-22.

117
00:13:29,836 --> 00:13:34,927
You can't become fully liberated until you are ethically completely purified.

118
00:13:34,908 --> 00:13:46,932
But you can't be ethically completely purified until you become liberated because you don't lose the core reason for our unwholesomeness until the point of liberation.

119
00:13:47,114 --> 00:13:51,221
And that is the sense of self or the notion of self.

120
00:13:51,261 --> 00:13:53,506
That doesn't go to the last bit.

121
00:13:53,486 --> 00:13:59,033
So it's an impossible situation to try and negotiate.

122
00:13:59,514 --> 00:14:08,202
One works on one side, purifying the heart, doing the right thing, and you keep on investigating the process.

123
00:14:08,864 --> 00:14:13,109
And at some point, hopefully, we'll find ourselves liberated from all suffering.

124
00:14:18,615 --> 00:14:22,278
The next one is this dogmatic fanaticism.

125
00:14:23,677 --> 00:14:28,605
And that of course again is based on misunderstanding upon delusion.

126
00:14:30,528 --> 00:14:40,807
And the Buddha points to three qualities when we have that sort of I'm right and everybody else is wrong and this is the way, this is the only way and lots of other stuff.

127
00:14:41,462 --> 00:14:44,125
And he says, first of all, there is the wrong view.

128
00:14:44,927 --> 00:14:54,116
Even if the wrong view is, this is the only way, or I'm right, and even if I'm right, I'll be wrong in saying that this is the only way.

129
00:14:54,158 --> 00:15:05,671
Although he does say it at the beginning of the discourse on how to establish right mindfulness.

130
00:15:05,711 --> 00:15:07,272
This is the one-way path.

131
00:15:07,293 --> 00:15:09,495
But he doesn't say this is the only way.

132
00:15:12,479 --> 00:15:16,465
By the way, it has been translated as that.

133
00:15:17,746 --> 00:15:31,447
But in fact, this ekayano, just as a little aside, this one-way path is meant to be as opposed to the two-way path, which is concentration plus insight practice.

134
00:15:31,466 --> 00:15:36,475
So what the Buddha is saying is that you don't need the concentration, you can just go straight with the insight practice.

135
00:15:36,495 --> 00:15:37,996
That's what it's referring to.

136
00:15:38,432 --> 00:15:43,861
But I think you'll find, for instance, Nyanaponika translating it as, this is the only way.

137
00:15:47,307 --> 00:15:51,634
So there is that misunderstanding, that wrong understanding.

138
00:15:52,135 --> 00:15:56,884
Then there's that emotional attachment to it, right?

139
00:15:57,144 --> 00:16:00,269
There's always a clinging around it.

140
00:16:00,870 --> 00:16:04,456
And that's what causes us to be angry when people disagree with us.

141
00:16:04,623 --> 00:16:05,504
Yeah.

142
00:16:05,524 --> 00:16:08,989
And of course, underneath all that, there is the sense of me.

143
00:16:09,330 --> 00:16:12,855
So I'm defining myself as this is me.

144
00:16:12,934 --> 00:16:14,356
This is my understanding.

145
00:16:14,376 --> 00:16:15,979
You know, I am a socialist.

146
00:16:16,078 --> 00:16:17,061
I am a capitalist.

147
00:16:17,201 --> 00:16:18,903
I am a Christian, et cetera, et cetera.

148
00:16:19,504 --> 00:16:28,898
And that connection of an identity brings about this emotional clinging to a particular view.

149
00:16:29,798 --> 00:16:32,722
And that's what causes us to get into arguments.

150
00:16:33,630 --> 00:16:34,566
etc.

151
00:16:34,972 --> 00:16:36,029
War, for instance.

152
00:16:37,192 --> 00:16:38,913
So how do we get out of that?

153
00:16:39,033 --> 00:16:42,557
Well, it's recognizing that we all have opinions.

154
00:16:42,937 --> 00:16:43,859
That's the way it is.

155
00:16:43,938 --> 00:16:45,921
Everybody has a view, an opinion.

156
00:16:46,501 --> 00:16:54,289
But when we actually begin to perceive that as a perspective, it does allow us to listen to other people.

157
00:16:54,330 --> 00:16:58,594
And it doesn't mean to say that we're going to be converted by them.

158
00:16:59,634 --> 00:17:03,578
It may be that it nuances what we actually believe.

159
00:17:04,079 --> 00:17:06,422
It may be that it changes what we actually believe.

160
00:17:06,402 --> 00:17:12,170
But in order to do that, you've got to let go of this business of I'm right and everybody else is wrong.

161
00:17:13,231 --> 00:17:17,498
So here is another thing that disappears with the Buddha.

162
00:17:18,419 --> 00:17:26,730
And it's interesting when, you know, people come to him and say, I believe this, you know, what do you believe?

163
00:17:26,770 --> 00:17:33,000
He always asks them first of all, well, to explain what they actually believe, what is their position.

164
00:17:33,165 --> 00:17:40,536
And then having heard it, he will then begin to question it and slowly undermine that position if it's wrong.

165
00:17:41,616 --> 00:17:54,913
And then once the person begins to feel that their argument isn't so strong, it's not right, that's when the Buddha pumps in the Four Noble Truths and away they go.

166
00:17:54,953 --> 00:18:01,603
So just to...

167
00:18:02,748 --> 00:18:06,933
go over those things, you know, go back to the original verse.

168
00:18:07,433 --> 00:18:12,480
So we're talking about our practice coming to a fulfillment, the journey's end.

169
00:18:13,962 --> 00:18:15,785
And we can be free of all sorrow.

170
00:18:16,385 --> 00:18:20,250
Sorrow is, I mean, won't go into it this evening, but sorrow is such a big word.

171
00:18:20,290 --> 00:18:28,501
It's not only grief about something, it's perhaps grief about something that we ought to have done, something that we did do, et cetera, et cetera.

172
00:18:30,102 --> 00:18:39,651
And of course it liberated in all ways and then that's defined in this particular verse as released from all the bonds.

173
00:18:41,032 --> 00:18:55,906
And these bonds we find are, you know, this acquisitiveness, this aversion and finally these two wrong understandings which are around rules and rituals and opinions.

174
00:18:59,953 --> 00:19:17,403
And the final result, of course, is to be liberated from all the emotional distress that comes from having these wrong views and these wrong attitudes.

175
00:19:17,963 --> 00:19:20,587
All that disappears.

176
00:19:21,650 --> 00:19:23,413
And that's the wonder of the practice.

177
00:19:26,093 --> 00:19:33,643
So that's the verse on number 90 on what it is to become an Arahant.

178
00:19:34,564 --> 00:19:45,739
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your devotion to practice you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

